  "issue_number": 107,
  "issue_title": "SwapConfirm allows reservation hijacking by a different user",
  "issue_body": "### Problem\nhandle_swap_confirm() does not verify that the confirming from_address matches the from_addr stored in the active reservation.\n\nThe validator reads get_reservation_data(miner), but does not enforce that the reservation owner and the confirmer are the same address. Instead, it trusts the from_address supplied in the incoming SwapConfirm request and uses it for transaction verification and vote_initiate().\n\n### Root Cause\nThe reservation already stores the user source address as from_addr, but handle_swap_confirm() never compares it against synapse.from_address.\n\nBecause that check is missing, confirmation is authorized by:\n- active reservation exists for the miner\n- submitted tx matches expected deposit address and amount\n- submitted tx sender matches the caller-supplied from_address\n\nIt is not authorized by the address that actually created the reservation.\n\n### Impact\nA malicious user can take over another user\u2019s active reservation.\nA concrete attack flow is:\n- User A reserves a miner.\n- The reservation becomes active.\n- User B sends the required source amount from User B\u2019s own address.\n- User B submits SwapConfirm with User B\u2019s from_address, proof, tx hash, and payout address.\n- Validators accept the confirm because the code never checks that the confirmer matches the reserved from_addr.\n- Validators call vote_initiate() using User B\u2019s addresses, even though User A created the reservation.\n\nThis breaks reservation ownership. An active reservation can be consumed by a different user than the one who reserved it, which is an authorization flaw and should be fixed urgently.",
